In France, the election has traditionally been a not-so-technological experience: voters are isolated in a cabinside and put in one on a pre-printed sheet of paper with the candidate they have chosen.
After those responsible verifies the identity of the voter, the voter lets the envelope fall into the urn and signs the vote sheet.
The French electoral law strictly codifies the procedures.
Since 1988, the ballots must be transparent so that the electors and observers can be witnesses that there is no envelope at the start of the vote and that other envelopes are not added to be those of the voters duly counted and authorized voters.
Candidates can send representatives to testify to each part of the procedure. In the evening, volunteers count the votes under strong supervision, following specific procedures.
