When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main and original group (for example, crossing a mountain range or a river, or migrating to a new island and cannot go back) they will often find themselves in a different environment than they had before.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need characteristics or adaptations different from those previously needed to be a strong competitor.
The original population has not changed at all, they continue to need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations were so different that they could no longer be considered the same species.
In this process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species. Speciation is a consequence that cannot be avoided and a very important part of evolution.
