The beginnings of Taiwan date back to the 15th century, when European sailors coined the island's name Ilha Formosa, or beautiful island.
In 1624, the Dutch East India Company established a base in southeast Taiwan, where it began the transformation of indigenous grain production practices and resorted to Chinese workers for rice and sugar plantations.
In 1683, Qing Dynasty forces (1644–1912) took control of the western and northern coasts of Taiwan, declaring Taiwan a province of the Qing Empire in 1885.
In 1895, after the defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), the Qing government signed the Treaty of Shimonoseki, by which it ceded the sovereignty of Taiwan to Japan, which would rule the island until 1945.
